## üõ†Ô∏è 3D Printing Procedure

This document describes the recommended process for manufacturing the 4‚ÄëDOF robotic arm using FDM 3D printing. All STL files are located in the /STL_Files directory of this repository.

### 1. Prerequisites
- 3D printer with a minimum build volume of 200 √ó 200 √ó 200 mm (examples: Creality Ender 3, Prusa i3).
- Filament: PLA+ or PETG is recommended.
  - Note: Standard PLA can be brittle for high‚Äëtorque joints; prefer PLA+ or PETG for improved durability.
- Slicer software: Cura, PrusaSlicer, or Simplify3D.

### 2. Slicer configuration
Use these baseline settings to balance strength, print time, and part accuracy. Adjust as needed for your machine and filament.

| Setting | Recommended value | Why |
|---|---:|---|
| Layer height | 0.20 mm | Good balance of surface quality and speed |
| Wall / Perimeter count | 3‚Äì4 | Most structural strength comes from the walls |
| Infill density | 30%‚Äì40% | Provides internal support for fasteners and load paths |
| Infill pattern | Gyroid or Cubic | More isotropic strength under multidirectional loads |
| Supports | Enabled (Tree/Organic or regular) | Needed for overhangs in joint connectors and housings |
| Build plate adhesion | Brim (or Skirt for smaller parts) | Prevents warping on large, flat surfaces |
| Print speed (load-bearing parts) | 40‚Äì60 mm/s | Slower improves dimensional accuracy and layer adhesion |
| Print speed (fine/gear parts) | 30‚Äì45 mm/s | Helps ensure proper gear meshing and fit |

